The C-dots have a very narrow size distribution with a clear lattice (Fig. 1
                        a) as shown in Fig. 1a. The measured d spacing is around 0.326 nm, corresponding to the (002) plane of the graphitic carbon [29]. The C-dots dispersed in methanol have an absorption spectrum covering from 300 to 600 nm with an emission peak of ∼540 nm (Fig. 2
                        ). The lifetime of the C-dots is around 7 ± 0.5 ns (Fig. 1c) [23]. The C-dots dispersed in methanol has a QY of 40%, similar with the reported value in the literature [23]. By tuning the concentration of C-dots in methanol solution, we can tune the n of C-dots/methanol solution, but in a very narrow range due to the low concentration of C-dots (<2 wt %). As shown in Fig. 2a, the n linearly increases from 1.3297 to 1.3389 as a function of C-dots concentration (from 0% to 1.98 wt %), due to the higher n value of carbon material compared to methanol. Further adding the PVP polymer (n of 1.5100), n increases to 1.4526 at the PVP concentration of 65.45 wt %. Similarly, n of the PVP/C-dots linearly increases as a function of PVP concentration (Fig. 2b). In fact, this property allows us to measure the unknown C-dots concentration in methanol with the calibration curve. With high PVP concentration (>50 wt %), the PVP methanol solution becomes very viscous and it is very difficult to inject such solution into glass mold at room temperature.
